Preheat your oven to 200°C. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1} (stalks and all). Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips. Pop the pepper onto a #baking tray{} and drizzle with @oil{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} then roast on the top shelf of your oven until charred and softened, ~{18-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pop a #saucepan{} over medium high-heat and add the @cumin seeds{1}(no oil). Stir and toast until fragrant, ~{1%minute}. Pour the @water{240%ml}(for the bulgur) into the saucepan with the cumin and bring to the boil. Stir in the @vegetable stock powder{1/2}, and @bulgur wheat{120%g}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}. Pop a #lid{} on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, line another #baking tray{} with #baking paper{} and drizzle with @oil{}. Place the @salmon fillets{2} on the tray skin-side down and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Sprinkle the @ground coriander{1} onto the flesh side. When the peppers have ~{15%minutes} left in the oven, slide the salmon tray in and roast until the salmon is cooked, ~{12-15%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The salmon is cooked when opaque all the way through.

While the salmon cooks, remove the @pistachios{25%g} from their shells. Discard the shells and finely chop the pistachios.

> Use a pestle and mortar if you have one.

Break the @feta cheese{100%g} into small chunks.

When the bulgur wheat is ready, use a #fork{} to fluff it up. Fold in the feta and parsley, taking care not to break up the feta too much. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{} if necessary. Share the bulgur between your bowls. Arrange the peppers and @wild rocket{40%g} on top of the bulgur.

When the salmon is cooked, remove from the oven and drizzle on the @honey{15%ml}. Spread the honey across the fish with the back of a #spoon{} and then sprinkle the pistachios onto the salmon. Carefully place on top of the layer of rocket. Dig in!